Here's the equivalent Drizzle ORM query:

```typescript
async getOne(id: string): Promise<UserWithRolesResponse | null> {
  const result = await db
    .select({
      id: users.id,
      email: users.email,
      firstName: users.firstName,
      lastName: users.lastName,
      phone: users.phone,
      isActive: users.isActive,
      isVerified: users.isVerified,
      createdAt: users.createdAt,
      updatedAt: users.updatedAt,
      deletedAt: users.deletedAt,
      roles: sql<Role[]>`json_agg(
        json_build_object(
          'id', ${roles.id},
          'name', ${roles.name},
          'permissions', (
            SELECT json_agg(
              json_build_object(
                'entity', permissions.entity,
                'action', permissions.action,
                'access', permissions.access
              )
            )
            FROM ${permissions}
            JOIN ${rolesToPermissions} ON ${rolesToPermissions.permissionId} = ${permissions.id}
            WHERE ${rolesToPermissions.roleId} = ${roles.id}
          )
        )
      )`
    })
    .from(users)
    .leftJoin(usersToRoles, eq(users.id, usersToRoles.userId))
    .leftJoin(roles, eq(usersToRoles.roleId, roles.id))
    .where(eq(users.id, id))
    .groupBy(
      users.id,
      users.email,
      users.firstName,
      users.lastName,
      users.phone,
      users.isActive,
      users.isVerified,
      users.createdAt,
      users.updatedAt,
      users.deletedAt
    );

  if (!result.length) {
    throw new Error(`User with id ${id} not found`);
  }

  return result[0];
}
```

You'll need to have your schema defined something like this:

```typescript
import { pgTable, text, timestamp, boolean } from 'drizzle-orm/pg-core';

export const users = pgTable('users', {
  id: text('id').primaryKey(),
  email: text('email').notNull(),
  firstName: text('first_name'),
  lastName: text('last_name'),
  phone: text('phone'),
  isActive: boolean('is_active').default(true),
  isVerified: boolean('is_verified').default(false),
  createdAt: timestamp('created_at').defaultNow(),
  updatedAt: timestamp('updated_at'),
  deletedAt: timestamp('deleted_at')
});

export const roles = pgTable('roles', {
  id: text('id').primaryKey(),
  name: text('name').notNull()
});

export const permissions = pgTable('permissions', {
  id: text('id').primaryKey(),
  entity: text('entity').notNull(),
  action: text('action').notNull(),
  access: text('access').notNull()
});

export const usersToRoles = pgTable('users_to_roles', {
  userId: text('user_id').references(() => users.id),
  roleId: text('role_id').references(() => roles.id)
});

export const rolesToPermissions = pgTable('roles_to_permissions', {
  roleId: text('role_id').references(() => roles.id),
  permissionId: text('permission_id').references(() => permissions.id)
});

// Type for the response
type UserWithRolesResponse = {
  id: string;
  email: string;
  firstName: string | null;
  lastName: string | null;
  phone: string | null;
  isActive: boolean;
  isVerified: boolean;
  createdAt: Date;
  updatedAt: Date | null;
  deletedAt: Date | null;
  roles: {
    id: string;
    name: string;
    permissions: {
      entity: string;
      action: string;
      access: string;
    }[];
  }[];
};
```

The main differences from the Prisma query are:

1. Drizzle requires explicit joins
2. Nested relations need to be handled using PostgreSQL's JSON aggregation functions
3. We need to explicitly group by the non-aggregated columns
4. The result comes as an array, so we need to check length and return the first item
5. Column names need to be explicitly referenced from the table objects

This query will give you the same nested structure as the Prisma query, with users, their roles, and the permissions for each role.
